sentences: From 1817, the Lortzing family were part of Josef Derossi ensemble in the Rhineland, treading the boards at Bonn, Düsseldorf, Barmen and Aachen.
On 30 January 1824 he married the actress Rosina Regine Ahles, with whom he subsequently had 11 children.
The couple belonged to the Hoftheater (court theatre) in Detmold from late 1826, which toured to Münster and Osnabrück.
On 3 November 1833 the young Lortzings gave their debut at the Leipziger Stadttheater.
Lortzing's parents had been members of this ensemble since 1832, under Friedrich Sebald Ringelhardt.

Here, Lortzing became a member of the artists' club "Tunnel unter der Pleisse" ("Tunnel under the Pleiße"), and in 1834 he became a member of the Leipzig Freemasons lodge "Balduin zur Linde" ("Balduin to the Linden Tree").
It premiered in Leipzig on 22 December 1837.
Lortzing himself sang the role of Peter Iwanow, but it did not make a major breakthrough until its Berlin performances in 1839, where it was much praised.
In 1844, Lortzing became Kapellmeister of the Leipzig Stadttheater.
After a quarrel with management, he was dismissed in April 1845 due to his "rheumatic troubles".
Between 1846 and 1848, Lortzing worked as Kapellmeister at the Theater an der Wien in Vienna.
At the behest of the Freedom Movement, he wrote text and music in 1848 for his political opera Regina, named after his wife.
In 1848 he lost his appointment and had to return to work as a touring actor to support his large family.
Finally in 1850, he became the Kapellmeister in Berlin at the newly opened Friedrich-Wilhelmstädtisches Theater.

On 20 January 1851, the night his musical comedy Die Opernprobe premiered in Frankfurt, Lortzing suffered a stroke at his home in Berlin and died without medical treatment on the morning of the following day, under huge stress and deeply in debt.
Lortzing's theatrical colleagues decorated his coffin with black, red and gold, a combination forbidden after 1848.
His first singspiel, Ali Pascha von Janina, appeared in 1824, but his fame as a musician rests chiefly upon the two operas Zar und Zimmermann (1837) and Der Wildschütz (1842).

sentences: Gustav Albert Lortzing (23 October 1801 – 21 January 1851) was a German composer, librettist, actor and singer.

His last full-length opera was an 1849 fairy-tale satire of the Prussian military state called Rolands Knappen (Roland's Squires), featuring the repeated line "And this is supposed to be a world order?"

On 20 January 1851, the night his musical comedy Die Opernprobe premiered in Frankfurt, Lortzing suffered a stroke at his home in Berlin and died without medical treatment on the morning of the following day, under huge stress and deeply in debt.
The opera soon appeared on all the stages of Germany, and today is regarded as one of the masterpieces of German comic opera.
Der Wildschütz was based on a comedy by August von Kotzebue, and was a satire on the unintelligent and exaggerated admiration for the highest beauty in art expressed by the bourgeois gentilhomme.
